  I(P_11, 2) =   2731 = J(13) = (2^13-(-1)^13)/3 ✓

CYCLE: I(C_m, 2) = j(m) = 2^m + (-1)^m [Jacobsthal-Lucas]
  I(C_ 3, 2) =      7 = 2^3+(-1)^3 = 7 ✓
  I(C_ 4, 2) =     17 = 2^4+(-1)^4 = 17 ✓
  I(C_ 5, 2) =     31 = 2^5+(-1)^5 = 31 ✓
  I(C_ 6, 2) =     65 = 2^6+(-1)^6 = 65 ✓
  I(C_ 7, 2) =    127 = 2^7+(-1)^7 = 127 ✓
  I(C_ 8, 2) =    257 = 2^8+(-1)^8 = 257 ✓
  I(C_ 9, 2) =    511 = 2^9+(-1)^9 = 511 ✓
  I(C_10, 2) =   1025 = 2^10+(-1)^10 = 1025 ✓
  I(C_11, 2) =   2047 = 2^11+(-1)^11 = 2047 ✓

COMPLETE: I(K_m, 2) = 1+2m [odd numbers]
  I(K_0, 2) = 1
  I(K_1, 2) = 3
  I(K_2, 2) = 5
  I(K_3, 2) = 7
  I(K_4, 2) = 9
  I(K_5, 2) = 11
  I(K_6, 2) = 13
  I(K_7, 2) = 15

GENERAL x: Fibonacci root at x → (1+√(1+4x))/2
  x=1: root = φ = 1.618  [Fibonacci]
  x=2: root = 2.000      [Jacobsthal — INTEGER!]
  x=3: root = 2.303      [Narayana]

  x=2 is the UNIQUE positive integer x where the Fibonacci root is an integer.
  Proof: (1+√(1+4x))/2 = k ⟹ 1+4x = (2k-1)² ⟹ x = k²-k = k(k-1)
  x=2 ⟹ k=2.  Next: x=6 ⟹ k=3, x=12 ⟹ k=4, ...
  But x=2 is the ONLY one where tournaments evaluate I(CG, x).

